Cite content {1: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy for medical and dental applications: a comprehensive review'. Abstract: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy is one of the most significant analytical techniques that has been developed in the past few decades. A broad range of biological and nonbiological applications ranging from an individual cell to organs and tissues has been investigated through NMR. Various aspects of this technique are still under research, and many functions of the NMR are still pending a better understanding and acknowledgment. Therefore, this review is aimed at providing a general overview of the main principles, types of this technique, and the advantages and disadvantages of NMR spectroscopy. In addition, an insight into the current uses of NMR in the field of medicine and dentistry and ongoing developments of NMR spectroscopy for future applications has been discussed.'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy for medical and dental applications: a comprehensive review' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 2: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 3: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 4: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Principles of nuclear magnetic resonance microscopy'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Principles of nuclear magnetic resonance microscopy' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 5: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 6: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Advances in low-field nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technologies applied for characterization of pore space inside rocks: a critical review'. Abstract: 'Low-field nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) has become a widely used technique for characterizing pore space in rocks. This paper provides a critical review of advances in low-field NMR technologies applied to pore space characterization. The review covers the principles of NMR relaxation and diffusion, experimental methods, and data analysis techniques. Applications include porosity, pore size distribution, permeability, and fluid typing. The paper also discusses the challenges and limitations of low-field NMR, such as the effects of internal gradients and paramagnetic minerals. Future developments in hardware and software are outlined.'", "The paper titled 'Advances in low-field nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technologies applied for characterization of pore space inside rocks: a critical review' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 7: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 8: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 9: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 10: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 11: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance T1–T2 spectra in heavy oil reservoirs'. Abstract: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) T1-T2 spectra are used to characterize heavy oil reservoirs. The T1-T2 maps provide information on fluid types and pore sizes. In heavy oil reservoirs, the NMR response is complicated by the high viscosity and complex composition of the oil. This study presents T1-T2 measurements on core samples from heavy oil reservoirs. The results show that heavy oil has distinct T1-T2 signatures that can be used to distinguish it from water and light oil. The T1/T2 ratio is correlated with oil viscosity. The study demonstrates the potential of T1-T2 maps for evaluating heavy oil reservoirs.'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance T1–T2 spectra in heavy oil reservoirs' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 12: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Characterization of fluid distributions in porous media by NMR techniques'. Abstract: 'NMR techniques are used to characterize fluid distributions in porous media. The study combines NMR relaxation and diffusion measurements to probe the spatial distribution of fluids. Experiments were performed on model porous media and rock cores with different fluid saturations. The results show that the NMR response is sensitive to the fluid distribution, with different relaxation and diffusion characteristics for different saturation states. The data are analyzed using theoretical models to infer the fluid distribution at the pore scale. The study demonstrates the potential of NMR for non-invasive characterization of multiphase fluid distributions.'", "The paper titled 'Characterization of fluid distributions in porous media by NMR techniques' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 13: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 14: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 15: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 16: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 17: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 18: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 19: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 20: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 21: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 22: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 23: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 24: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 25: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 26: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of internal magnetic-field gradients on nuclear-magnetic-resonance measurements and nuclear-magnetic-resonance-based pore-network characterization'. Abstract: 'The effect of internal magnetic-field gradients on NMR measurements and pore-network characterization is investigated. Internal gradients arise from susceptibility differences between the solid matrix and pore fluids. They affect relaxation times and diffusion measurements. The study uses numerical simulations and experiments on rock cores to quantify the effects. The results show that internal gradients can lead to errors in pore size estimation and permeability prediction. A method for correcting NMR data for internal gradients is proposed. The study improves the accuracy of NMR-based pore-network characterization.'", "The paper titled 'Effect of internal magnetic-field gradients on nuclear-magnetic-resonance measurements and nuclear-magnetic-resonance-based pore-network characterization' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 27: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of mineral composition on transverse relaxation time distributions and MR imaging of tight rocks from offshore Ireland'. Abstract: 'Tight reservoir rocks are characterized by low porosity and permeability, which complicates fluid flow and production. Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is a widely used technique to assess pore space and fluid properties in such rocks. However, the interpretation of NMR data in tight rocks is challenging due to the complex pore structure and the presence of different minerals. In this study, we investigate the effect of mineral composition on transverse relaxation time (T2) distributions and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of tight rocks from offshore Ireland. We conducted NMR measurements on a suite of rock samples with varying mineralogy, including quartz, clay, and carbonate. The results show that the T2 distributions are significantly affected by the presence of paramagnetic minerals such as clays and iron-bearing carbonates, which enhance relaxation rates. MRI images reveal heterogeneous fluid distributions influenced by mineralogy and pore structure. This study provides insights into the interpretation of NMR data in tight rocks and highlights the importance of considering mineral composition when assessing reservoir quality.'", "The paper titled 'Effect of mineral composition on transverse relaxation time distributions and MR imaging of tight rocks from offshore Ireland' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 28: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 29: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 30: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 31: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 32: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 33: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 34: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 35: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 36: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 37: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 38: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance surface relaxivity and its advanced application in calculating pore size distributions'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Nuclear magnetic resonance surface relaxivity and its advanced application in calculating pore size distributions' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 39: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 40: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 41: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 42: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Low-field nuclear magnetic resonance characterization of carbonate and sandstone reservoirs from rock spring uplift of wyoming'. Abstract: 'Low-field NMR is used to characterize carbonate and sandstone reservoirs from the Rock Spring Uplift of Wyoming. NMR T2 relaxation time measurements provide information on pore size distributions and fluid saturations. The results are compared with conventional core analysis. The study shows that NMR can distinguish between different pore types and fluid populations. The NMR data are used to estimate permeability and to evaluate reservoir quality. The study demonstrates the value of low-field NMR for reservoir characterization.'", "The paper titled 'Low-field nuclear magnetic resonance characterization of carbonate and sandstone reservoirs from rock spring uplift of wyoming' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 43: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Effect of paramagnetic species on T 1, T 2 and T 1 /T 2 NMR relaxation times of liquids in porous CuSO 4 /Al 2 O 3'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Effect of paramagnetic species on T 1, T 2 and T 1 /T 2 NMR relaxation times of liquids in porous CuSO 4 /Al 2 O 3' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 44: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A laboratory study to determine the effect of iron oxides on proton NMR measurements'. Abstract: 'Iron oxides in rocks and sediments affect proton NMR measurements by enhancing surface relaxation. This laboratory study investigates the effect of iron oxides on NMR T2 relaxation times. Synthetic samples with controlled iron oxide content and distribution were prepared. NMR measurements show that iron oxides reduce T2 relaxation times and can mask the pore size information. The effect depends on the iron oxide concentration and its proximity to the pore surface. The study provides insights into the interpretation of NMR data in iron-rich formations.'", "The paper titled 'A laboratory study to determine the effect of iron oxides on proton NMR measurements' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 45: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 46: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 47: ('[NOTEXIST]', 