ize distribution, wettability, and fluid saturation. Novel methods, including T1-T2 maps and high-field NMR, are discussed. The review identifies future research directions for NMR in shales, including the integration of NMR with other techniques and the development of new pulse sequences.'", "The paper titled 'NMR application in unconventional shale reservoirs – a new porous media research frontier' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 70: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 71: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 72: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 73: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 74: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 75: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Application of nuclear magnetic resonance permeability models in tight reservoirs'. Abstract: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) permeability models are evaluated for tight reservoirs. The study compares different NMR permeability models, including the Schlumberger-Doll Research (SDR) model and the Timur-Coates model, using data from tight sandstone and carbonate cores. The results show that the accuracy of the models depends on the pore structure and the presence of microporosity. Modifications to the models are proposed to improve permeability estimation in tight reservoirs. The study provides guidance for selecting and calibrating NMR permeability models for tight reservoirs.'", "The paper titled 'Application of nuclear magnetic resonance permeability models in tight reservoirs' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 76: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 77: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Wettability quantification in mixed-wet rocks using a new NMR-based method'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Wettability quantification in mixed-wet rocks using a new NMR-based method' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 78: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Downhole wettability: the potential of NMR'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Downhole wettability: the potential of NMR' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 79: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 80: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 81: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 82: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 83: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Integrated petrophysics and geosteering reservoir characterization in the initial development phase of a carbonate reservoir - Campos Basin, Offshore Brazil'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Integrated petrophysics and geosteering reservoir characterization in the initial development phase of a carbonate reservoir - Campos Basin, Offshore Brazil' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 84: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 85: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 86: ("There is a paper. Title: 'The influence factors of NMR logging porosity in complex fluid reservoir'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'The influence factors of NMR logging porosity in complex fluid reservoir' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 87: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 88: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A laboratory study of NMR relaxation times and pore coupling in heterogeneous media'. Abstract: 'NMR relaxation times in heterogeneous media are affected by pore coupling due to diffusion. This laboratory study investigates the effects of pore coupling on NMR T2 relaxation times in unconsolidated sediments with different pore structures. The results show that pore coupling can cause the relaxation time distribution to deviate from the pore size distribution, especially when the pores are well connected. The degree of coupling depends on the diffusion coefficient, pore size, and surface relaxivity. The study provides insights into the interpretation of NMR data in heterogeneous media and the conditions under which pore coupling is important.'", "The paper titled 'A laboratory study of NMR relaxation times and pore coupling in heterogeneous media' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 89: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A laboratory study of NMR relaxation times in unconsolidated heterogeneous sediments'. Abstract: 'This laboratory study investigates NMR relaxation times in unconsolidated heterogeneous sediments. The sediments have different grain size distributions and mineralogies. NMR T2 relaxation time measurements were performed on water-saturated samples. The results show that the T2 distribution reflects the pore size distribution, but is also affected by the presence of paramagnetic minerals and the surface relaxivity. The study provides a database of NMR relaxation times for different sediment types and discusses the implications for NMR logging in unconsolidated aquifers.'", "The paper titled 'A laboratory study of NMR relaxation times in unconsolidated heterogeneous sediments' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 90: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A finite element approach to forward modeling of nuclear magnetic resonance measurements in coupled pore systems'. Abstract: 'A finite element approach is developed for forward modeling of NMR measurements in coupled pore systems. The model solves the Bloch-Torrey equations for magnetization evolution in complex pore geometries. The approach accounts for diffusion coupling between pores and surface relaxation. The model is validated by comparison with analytical solutions and experimental data. The finite element method enables realistic simulations of NMR responses in rocks and other porous media. The model can be used to interpret NMR data and to optimize pulse sequences.'", "The paper titled 'A finite element approach to forward modeling of nuclear magnetic resonance measurements in coupled pore systems' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 91: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 92: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 93: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 94: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 95: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 96: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 97: ("There is a paper. Title: 'An NMR-based clay content evaluation method for tight oil reservoirs'. Abstract: 'Clay content is an important parameter for evaluating tight oil reservoirs. This study presents an NMR-based method for evaluating clay content. The method uses the fact that clay-bound water has short T2 relaxation times. The NMR T2 distribution is decomposed into components corresponding to clay-bound water and movable fluids. The amplitude of the short T2 component is correlated with clay content. The method is applied to tight oil reservoir cores and validated with X-ray diffraction data. The NMR method provides a quick and non-destructive way to estimate clay content.'", "The paper titled 'An NMR-based clay content evaluation method for tight oil reservoirs' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 98: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 99: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 100: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 101: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 102: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 103: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 104: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 105: ("There is a paper. Title: 'NMR logging to estimate hydraulic conductivity in unconsolidated aquifers'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'NMR logging to estimate hydraulic conductivity in unconsolidated aquifers' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 106: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 107: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 108: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 109: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Quantitative remaining oil interpretation using magnetic resonance: from the laboratory to the pilot'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Quantitative remaining oil interpretation using magnetic resonance: from the laboratory to the pilot' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 110: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Quantitative in situ enhanced oil recovery monitoring using nuclear magnetic resonance'. Abstract: 'Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is used to monitor enhanced oil recovery (EOR) processes in situ. The study demonstrates quantitative NMR measurements of oil saturation during water flooding and polymer flooding in core samples. NMR T2 relaxation time distributions provide information on oil distribution and mobilization. The results show that NMR can track changes in oil saturation with high sensitivity and spatial resolution. The method is applied to different EOR processes and provides insights into recovery mechanisms. NMR monitoring has potential applications in laboratory core floods and field pilots.'", "The paper titled 'Quantitative in situ enhanced oil recovery monitoring using nuclear magnetic resonance' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 111: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Monitoring chemical EOR processes'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Monitoring chemical EOR processes' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 112: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 113: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 114: ("There is a paper. Title: 'A review of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technology applied in the characterization of polymer gels for petroleum reservoir conformance control'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'A review of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technology applied in the characterization of polymer gels for petroleum reservoir conformance control' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 115: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 116: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 117: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 118: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 119: ("There is a paper. Title: 'CO2 flooding enhanced oil recovery evaluated using magnetic resonance imaging technique'. Abstract: 'CO2 flooding enhanced oil recovery (EOR) is evaluated using magnetic resonance imaging (MRI). The experiments simulate CO2 injection in sandstone cores under reservoir conditions. MRI provides images of oil saturation during the flood, showing the displacement patterns and the remaining oil distribution. The results show that CO2 flooding recovers significant oil, but some oil remains trapped in smaller pores. The MRI data are used to quantify the recovery efficiency and to identify the mechanisms of oil mobilization. The study demonstrates the value of MRI for EOR research.'", "The paper titled 'CO2 flooding enhanced oil recovery evaluated using magnetic resonance imaging technique' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 120: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 121: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Polymer flooding enhanced oil recovery evaluated with magnetic resonance imaging and relaxation time measurements'. Abstract: 'Polymer flooding is an enhanced oil recovery (EOR) method that improves sweep efficiency by increasing the viscosity of the injected water. This study uses magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and relaxation time measurements to evaluate polymer flooding in core samples. MRI provides spatial maps of oil and water saturation during the flood. Relaxation time measurements provide information on fluid-pore interactions. The results show that polymer flooding recovers more oil than water flooding, especially from heterogeneous regions. The MRI and NMR data provide insights into the mechanisms of polymer flooding at the pore scale.'", "The paper titled 'Polymer flooding enhanced oil recovery evaluated with magnetic resonance imaging and relaxation time measurements' with the given abstract could be cited in the paper: 'A review on the applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) in the oil and gas industry: laboratory and field-scale measurements'."), 122: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 123: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 124: ('[NOTEXIST]', '[NOTEXIST]'), 125: ("There is a paper. Title: 'Experimental investigation on CO 2 injection in block M'. Abstract: 'None'", "The paper titled 'Experimental investigation on CO 2 injection in block M' with th